(Beginner) Quest 2 - Learning Core Concepts & Exploring The Hedera Ecosystem
Introduction
In this quest, we’ll be covering further core concepts in Hedera such as nodes, transactions, accounts, keys, among many others. We’ll also be getting our feet wet in the Hedera ecosystem! This entails exploring some commonly used Hedera dApps, creating a Hedera Developer Portal account and setting up our first Hedera wallet. We’ll also be seeing how we can use the HashPack wallet to transfer HBAR from one account to another.
For queries on this quest, join our Discord, head to the #hedera-helpdesk channel and look for this quest's post.
Learning Outcomes
By the end of this quest, you will be able to:
  • Describe core concepts in Hedera. These include consensus & mirror nodes, the HBAR token, accounts, transactions and queries & confirmations
  • Describe the difference between state and history
  • Be familiar with some examples of decentralized applications on the Hedera network
  • Create a Hedera Developer Portal testnet account
  • Create a HashPack wallet and transfer HBAR tokens

Quest Walkthrough
Step 1: Consensus & Mirror Nodes
The Hedera network is powered by nodes that ensure the security, scalability, and reliability of the distributed ledger. Node operators are responsible for running the node, maintaining uptime, and participating in consensus. The Hedera network consists of two types of nodes, consensus nodes and mirror nodes. Let’s find out more about each type of node as well as their differences below.
Consensus Nodes
Hedera consensus nodes aka mainnet nodes are a type of node in the Hedera network that participates in the consensus process. Consensus nodes receive transactions, contribute to the Hashgraph consensus and store the public ledger’s latest state. Consensus nodes are currently permissioned and operated by the Hedera Governing Council - this means that only selected entities can be consensus nodes.

Mirror Nodes
Hedera mirror nodes are a type of node in the Hedera public network that replicates the ledger in real-time, without participating in the consensus process. They are read-only nodes that provide access to the verifiable data on the public ledger. In addition, there are infrastructure companies that provide paid versions of the mirror nodes for businesses to utlise and build decentralized applications. Although mirror nodes do not participate in the Hashgraph consensus, they receive ledger information from consensus nodes. 

Developers can communicate with mirror nodes through the Hedera mainnet, testnet, and previewnet REST APIs. The mirror node will give developers access to ledger data. In addition to providing access to the ledger data, mirror nodes can provide additional functionality, such as indexing the ledger data, making it easier to search and query. This functionality can be useful for applications that need to perform complex queries on the ledger data, such as for analytics purposes or reporting tools.
Step 2: HBAR Token
HBAR is the native, energy-efficient cryptocurrency of the public Hedera network. There are two main functions that the HBAR token plays in the Hedera network - network fuel and network protection.
Network Fuel
HBAR is used by developers to pay for network services such as transferring HBAR, minting fungible and non-fungible tokens, interacting with smart contracts, logging data etc. Essentially, every transaction that occurs in the network will require an amount of HBAR to be used as payment fees to compensate validator nodes for their bandwidth, computation resources and storage.

Network Protection
Since Hedera is a proof-of-stake network, staking HBAR to nodes improves the security of the network. When HBAR is staked to network nodes, they have weighted voting on consensus for validating transactions. Weighted voting makes it expensive (and therefore difficult) for a bad actor to maliciously affect consensus as the bad actor would have to own and stake over one-third of the network’s total supply of HBAR.
Step 3: Accounts - Core Components
Accounts are the central starting point for Hedera. Accounts are stored on the public ledger and hold HBAR; which as we’ve learnt in the previous step, are mainly used to pay for the transaction fees as well as for bolstering the security of the network. Accounts can be created, updated, or deleted. With regards to account creation, it can be done by one of two methods - either by using an existing account or by using an alias. 
There are several components to an account. Let’s go through each of them:

Account ID
Each Hedera account is represented by an account ID. It is used to reference specific accounts in transactions and queries. Account IDs follow the format x.y.z (e.g. 0.0.3) where:
  1. x: shard number (shardId), defaults to 0 as Hedera only performs in one shard
  2. y: realm number (realmId), defaults to 0 as realms are not supported yet
  3. z: account number or account alias, more information can be found below!

Account Number
Every Hedera account is assigned a unique, immutable, system-generated account number upon creation. This non-negative 8-byte number is used to identify the account in all transaction and query requests on Hedera. The format of the account number ID is <shardNum>.<realmNum>.<accountNum> e.g. (0.0.10), and it's provided in the transaction receipt or transaction record associated with the account's creation.

An account alias will be given when the account is created by transferring an asset to an account alias via the auto account creation flow. The alias can be of type public key or Ethereum Virtual Machine (EVM) address. 
  • A public key account alias looks like: <shardNum>.<realNum>.<alias> where alias is public key of an ECDSA secp256k1 or ED25519 key type.
  • An EVM address account alias looks like: <shardNum>.<realNum>.<alias> where alias is an EVM address.

It’s important to note that ALL accounts have an Account Number alias which is a hex-encoded form of the account number prefixed with 20 bytes of zeros. The account number alias does not contain the shard ID and realm ID and this account property is not stored in consensus node state.

Account Memo
A memo is a brief note associated with an account in the ledger state, viewable via a network explorer. Limited to 100 characters, this account memo can be modified or deleted anytime, with changes necessitating the account key's signature.

Account Nonce
On Hedera, accounts can process EthereumTransaction types via the EVM on a consensus node. An account's nonce, set to zero by default, is an increasing count of EthereumTransaction types submitted by the account.

Automatic Token Associations
Hedera accounts usually need to approve custom tokens before they can be transferred. This involves the receiving account signing a transaction for token association. However, with the automatic token association feature, up to 5,000 tokens can be approved automatically without manual preauthorization. For accounts needing to hold more than 5,000 custom tokens, each additional token must be manually approved. The total number of tokens an account can hold is limitless, and the settings for this feature can be altered after initial setup.

Balances
Upon creating a new Hedera account, an initial HBAR balance can be allocated. This is optional and the amount, if any, is deducted from the account funding the creation. Hedera accounts can store balances of HBAR, as well as fungible and non-fungible tokens (NFTs). These balances can be seen on a network explorer and accessed through mirror node REST APIs or consensus nodes.

Keys
Every Hedera account needs at least one key when created, which, if absent, leads to transaction rejection. The key holders can authorize token transfers and modify account properties, including balance, memo, keys, etc. Optionally, accounts can have multiple keys, resulting in a multi-signature account where transactions require more than one signature. The specific signing requirements depend on the account's key structure. For more on key structures and types, refer here.

Receiver Signature Required
Accounts on Hedera have the optional feature to mandate the account's signature for any transactions depositing tokens. By default, this feature is deactivated. If activated, the account's signature is compulsory for transactions depositing tokens. This setting can be changed after the account is created.
Step 4: Accounts - Additional Components
Besides the core components of an account as listed in the previous step, there are a few additional concepts regarding an account. Additional account components include:
Staking
Staking in Hedera involves linking an account's HBAR balance to a network node to enhance network security. This process doesn't consider custom tokens the account holds. Staked accounts can earn HBAR rewards, contributing to network security. This feature is also applicable to contracts. For detailed information about the staking rewards program refer here.

Staking Information
The network stores the staking metadata for an account and contract accounts. This information is returned in account information query requests (AccountInfoQuery or ContractInfoQuery). The staking metadata for an account includes the following information:
  • decline_reward: Whether or not the account declined to earn staking rewards
  • stake_period_start: The staking period during which either the staking settings for this account or contract changed (such as starting staking or changing staked_node_id) or the most recent reward was earned, whichever is later. If this account or contract is not currently staked to a node, then this field is not set. The stake period is 24 hours, starting UTC midnight.
  • pending_reward: The amount in tinybars that will be received in the next staking reward payment
  • staked_to_me: The total tinybar balance of all accounts staked to this account
  • staked_id: ID of the account or node to which this account or contract is staking
  • staked_account_id: The account to which this account or contract is staking to
  • staked_node_id: The ID of the node this account or contract is staked to

Auto Renewals & Expiration
Hedera accounts, like other entities, use network storage and will incur a renewal fee to cover storage costs. While not currently active, once enabled, accounts must maintain enough funds to pay these fees. The renewal fees are charged at a fixed interval (auto-renew period), and if an account lacks sufficient HBAR balance, it will be suspended for a week before deletion. However, an account can be renewed during this suspension period. Note that this feature is NOT YET IMPLEMENTED on the network, i.e. accounts currently do NOT expire.
Step 5: Transactions
Transactions are requests sent by a client to a consensus node in the network to be processed. As mentioned in the earlier steps, every transaction has an associated transaction fee that is required as payment to the Hedera network.
A transaction generally includes the following:
  1. Node Account - the account of the node that the transaction is being sent to (e.g. 0.0.3)
  2. Transaction ID - the unique identifier assigned to every transaction that is submitted to the network. More information is covered below
  3. Transaction Fee - the maximum fee the paying account is willing to pay for the transaction
  4. Valid Duration - the number of seconds a transaction should remain valid before it expires. All transactions have a validity duration of up to 180 seconds
  5. Memo - a string of text up to 100 bytes of data (optional)
  6. Transaction - the type of request - for e.g. transferring HBAR
  7. Signatures - result of verifying the authenticity of a transaction. The paying account will sign the transaction as authorization (more signatures may be present as well)

Transaction ID
Let’s dive a bit deeper into transaction IDs! Each transaction has a unique transaction ID. The transaction ID is used for purposes such as obtaining receipts, record and state proofs, as well as internally by the network for detection purposes when duplicate transactions are submitted.

The transaction ID is composed by using the transaction valid start time and the account ID of the account that is paying for the transaction; it follows the following format - accountID@transactionValidStart e.g. 0.0.9401@1598924675.82525000. The transaction valid start time is the time the transaction begins to be processed on the network. The transaction valid start time can be set to a future date/time. 

As mentioned earlier in this step, transactions have a validity duration of up to 180 seconds. This means that the transaction has up to 180 seconds to be accepted by one of the nodes in the network. If the transaction is not accepted in this timeframe, the transaction will expire and the transaction will have to be created, signed, and submitted again.
Step 6: Nested Transactions
Now that we know more about transactions, let’s explore the concept of nested transactions! A nested transaction is a type of transaction that involves grouping multiple transactions together and treating them as a single unit. This is typically used when a user wants to bundle several transactions into one single transaction. 

The top-level transaction that a user submits is a parent transaction. Each subsequent transaction the parent transaction triggers as a result of the execution of the parent transaction is a child transaction.

Nested Transaction IDs
Parent and child transactions share the payer account ID and transaction valid start timestamp. The child transaction IDs have an additional nonce value that represents the order in which child transactions were executed. The parent transaction has a nonce value of 0. The nonce value of child transactions increments by 1 for each child transaction executed as a result of the parent transaction. It follows the following format:
  • Parent Transaction ID: payerAccountId@transactionValidStart
  • Child Transaction ID: payerAccountId@transactionValidStart/nonce
Examples:
  • Parent Transaction ID: 0.0.2252@1640119571.329880313
  • Child 1 Transaction ID: 0.0.2252@1640119571.329880313/1
  • Child 2 Transaction ID: 0.0.2252@1640119571.329880313/2

Nested Transaction Records
Nested transaction records are returned by requesting the record for the parent transaction and setting setIncludeChildren(<value>) to true. Child transaction records include the parent consensus timestamp and the child transaction ID. However, in some cases, it is possible for a child transaction to be triggered before the parent transaction is added to the network. In cases like this, the parent consensus timestamp in the child transaction won’t be filled.

Nested Transaction Receipts
Nested transaction receipts can be returned by requesting the parent transaction receipt and setting the boolean value equal to true to return all child transaction receipts.

Child Transaction Fees
The transaction fee for the child transaction is included in the record of the parent transaction. The transaction fee will return zero in the child transaction.
Step 7: Scheduled Transactions
Another interesting type of transaction that the Hedera network allows for are scheduled transactions! A scheduled transaction is a transaction with the ability to collect the required signatures on a Hedera network in preparation for its execution. Unlike the other Hedera transactions we covered in the previous steps, scheduled transactions allow you to queue a transaction for execution in the event you do not have all the required signatures for the network to immediately process the transaction. 
When a scheduled transaction is created, the network creates a scheduling entity. These scheduled entities receive an entity ID (just like accounts, tokens, etc) called a schedule ID. The scheduled transaction can be referred to as the outer transaction while the scheduled transaction can be referenced as the inner transaction.

Signatures are appended to that transaction by submitting the ScheduleSign transaction. The ScheduleSign transaction requires the schedule ID of the scheduled transaction that the signatures will be appended to. A scheduled transaction has 30 minutes to collect all required signatures before the scheduled transaction can be executed; failing which, it’ll be deleted from the network.

Scheduled transactions can be queried using ScheduleGetInfo and will return the following information:
  1. Schedule ID
  2. Account ID that created the schedule transaction
  3. Account ID that paid for the creation of the schedule transaction
  4. Transaction body of the inner transaction
  5. Transaction ID of the inner transaction
  6. Current list of signatures
  7. Admin key (if any)
  8. Expiration time
  9. Timestamp of when the transaction was deleted (if true)

Scheduled Transaction ID
As covered in earlier steps, Hedera transaction IDs are composed of the accountID and transaction valid timestamp. However, for scheduled transactions, there is an additional ?schedule at the end of transaction ID e.g. 0.0.1.2.3.4@1615422161.673238162?scheduled. The transaction ID of the scheduled (inner) transaction inherits the transaction valid start time and account ID from the scheduled (outer) transaction.

Scheduled Transaction Receipts
The transaction receipt for a scheduled transaction contains the new schedule entity ID and the scheduled transaction ID. The schedule transaction ID used to request records for the inner transaction upon successful execution. Note that the schedule entity ID is a unique identifier for the schedule whereas the schedule transaction ID is the ID of the transaction that will be executed by the scheduled transaction.

Scheduled Transaction Records
Transaction records are created when any of the following situations occur: 1/ scheduled transaction is created, 2/ signatures are appended, 3/ scheduled transaction is executed and 4/ if the scheduled transaction is deleted by the user. The record of a scheduled transaction includes the ID of the schedule the record is associated with. We can query for transaction records of inner transactions after their successful execution using any of the following methods:
  • Poll the network for the specified scheduled transaction ID. Once the scheduled transaction executes the scheduled transaction successfully, request the record for the scheduled transaction using the scheduled transaction ID
  • Query a Hedera mirror node for the scheduled transaction ID
  • Run your own mirror node and query for the scheduled transaction ID
Step 8: Queries & Confirmations
Queries In Hedera, a query is a request for information from the network. Queries are processed only by the single node to which they are sent. Queries are subject to fees, which are paid with HBAR. The user will not receive a refund if a user overpaid for the query. To determine the appropriate fee for a query, the user can ask a node for the cost by using the COST_ANSWER query (this is a free service).

Confirmations
Once a transaction has been submitted to the network, the user may seek confirmation of it being successfully processed. There are three types of confirmations available:
  1. Receipts - provides minimal information; it only provides information describing whether or not the transaction was successfully processed in consensus. Receipts are generated by default (it’s free) and are persisted for 3 minutes
  2. Records - provides detailed information on transactions such as consensus timestamps or results of a smart contract call. Similar to receipts, records are generated by default and are persisted for 3 minutes. Longer lived records (24 hours) are created if a crypto transfer transaction surpasses a threshold defined on the accounts involved
  3. State Proofs (coming soon) - In addition, when querying for a record, users can use their client to ask for state proofs. A state-proof has access to information about that record in the consensus state. This information includes signatures of most of the network nodes. Because a supermajority of the network cryptographically signs state proofs, they are secure and potentially admissible in a court of law
Step 9: State & History
State machines are mechanisms that are used to manage the state of the ledger and ensure that transactions are processed in a consistent manner. They are used to process transactions and update the ledger. They are also replicated across multiple nodes so that nodes are able to maintain a consistent state of the ledger. 
State vs History
The latest state vs the history of transactions are two different data structures with different properties. The state represents the current values of all the assets and accounts on the network. State is mutable, which means it is updated as new transactions are processed and applied to the ledger.

On the other hand, the history of transactions represents a record of all the transactions that have been submitted to the network and applied to the ledger. It is seen as immutable and irreversible contrary to state, which is mutable. Overall, both the state of the ledger and the history of transactions are important components of the Hedera network.

Nodes Maintain State & History
There are 3 functions performed by a node: 1/ contribute to consensus, 2/ persist history of transactions, and 3/ persist state. But nodes cannot optimally perform all roles because of their limited resources. So they make choices regarding which functions to prioritise…

Mainnet Nodes
For Hedera mainnet nodes, contributing to consensus and persisting state are the priorities. The hashgraph, which carries within it all the transactions that change the state, continuously removes old transaction information after it has been assigned a place in consensus order. Mainnet consensus nodes can safely delete older portions of the hashgraph as they can be confident that the transactions contained in those portions have been applied to the state of the ledger and are not subject to change because the algorithm delivers finality. 

Once a transaction has been assigned a timestamp, ordered and applied to the state, there is no chance that it will be reversed. Consequently, there is no need to keep historical transactions. To prevent such historical transactions from filling up the node’s storage, consensus nodes delete historical transactions.

Mirror Nodes
We learnt that the mainnet nodes delete historical transactions in a bid to save storage space. However, there is a need to preserve history. For example, an auditor might want to review the transaction history or trace the flow activity on the network. This is where the mirror nodes come in - their priorities are to persist history of transactions and persist state. They can choose whether to store all history, no history, or possibly only a fraction of the history, etc. 

Mirror nodes also store information that allows them to prove that their history is correct, even for some kinds of partial histories. So a malicious mirror node is unable to lie about what it is storing. Overall, a client seeking a transaction from the past would query through the mirror node for the record of that transaction. As the burden of storing history is borne by mirrors and not mainnet nodes, the latter can be optimized for the more fundamental role of consensus and state storage.
Step 10: Exploring The Hedera Ecosystem
Similar to other blockchain ecosystems, Hedera has a variety of dApps and projects that serve different purposes. Let’s take a look at some of these projects! Please note that this is not a full project list and many other projects exist on Hedera. The projects below are just a few examples within each category.
dApps
Calaxy - decentralizing social media and empowering creators to connect and provide services directly to their followers

SaucerSwap - the pioneering decentralized exchange (DEX) on Hedera; here you can swap tokens, provide liquidity to swap pools and yield farm

Hashport - this dApp is a public utility dApp that facilitates the transfer of tokens across networks in a quick, secure and cost-effective way

Zuse Market - the leading NFT marketplace on Hedera; here you can buy and sell Hedera NFTs as well as get access to a rich variety of features including NFT auctioning, statistical analysis, launchpads and many others

Enterprise Applications
TYMLEZ - carbon offset reporting and guarantee of origin solutions

AdsDax - decentralized advertising platform

Omni by SUKU - verify product authenticity throughout a supply chain

Wallets & Custody
HashPack - Hedera ecosystem browser extension and mobile wallet. We’ll be exploring this in the subsequent steps of this quest

Blade - Hedera ecosystem browser extension and mobile wallet

Network Explorers
HashScan - Hedera network(s) explorer built by Swirlds Labs

Hgraph.io - blazing fast GraphQL API for the Hedera network

Tooling & Integration
Magic - Web3 wallet onboarding and authentication SDKs

Banxa - KYC and global on/off-ramps for stablecoins and crypto

Again, there are many other projects (as well as categories of projects) that exist on Hedera, the few listed above are just some examples. If you’re interested in finding out more, you can refer here for an ecosystem explorer prepared by Hedera Foundation.
Step 11: Creating a Testnet Account on Hedera Developer Portal
In this quest as well as the subsequent quests, we’ll be needing Hedera testnet tokens since we’ll be interacting with the Hedera testnet. Recall that transactions with the network require tokens to pay for gas fees. 
In other blockchain networks, we typically get testnet tokens via a faucet. However, in Hedera, instead of using a faucet, we create a testnet account on the Hedera Developer Portal. Every 24 hours, your testnet account will have its balance topped up to 10,000 testnet HBAR tokens. 

Follow the steps below to create a testnet account:
  1. Head to the Hedera Developer Portal
  2. Sign up for an account. You’ll need to verify the OTP with your email
  3. After you’ve set up your profile, you’ll be redirected to the home screen. Press on ‘CREATE ACCOUNT’, you should get an output similar to the image below



And as simple as that, we’ve created a ECDSA based testnet account on the Hedera Developer Portal. However, the HashPack wallet which we’ll be using in the next step as well as the subsequent quests only supports ED25519 based accounts, thus you’ll need to press on the ‘CREATE ED25519 ACCOUNT’ button to generate an ED25519 based account. Once that’s done, your screen should look similar to the image below.



If you have an existing Hedera Developer Portal account, feel free to log in to that account instead. However, note that Hedera schedules testnet resets every quarter to ensure a better developer experience by decluttering the network of stale data, removing spam, and helping maintain the system over time. 

If you created your Hedera Developer Portal account before 27th July 2023 (the date of the most recent testnet reset), you’ll need to visit Hedera Developer Portal to get your new testnet account ID. Note that your public and private keys will remain the same.
Step 12: Creating a Wallet Using HashPack
Now let’s create another wallet. This time, let’s use the HashPack wallet to do so. Follow the steps below to create a wallet using HashPack:
  1. Head to the download page of HashPack here
  2. As a browser extension, HashPack currently only supports Google Chrome. If you’re a Google Chrome user, then you can press on ‘Install on Chrome’ to have it installed. Otherwise, you can proceed with ‘Launch Web App’ for the browser version of HashPack
  3. Once HashPack is opened (either via the Chrome extension or the web app), press on ‘Create a new wallet’ and enter a password of your choice
  4. Tick the ‘Testnet account’ checkbox and press on ‘Advanced wallet creation’
  5. Make sure to store your seed phrase in a secure location. On the next screen, fill up the phrase verification check
  6. Lastly, give your wallet a name of your choice, select ‘US Dollar’ (should be the default option) and press on ‘Create Wallet’. You’ll be prompted again to ensure that you’ve saved your seed phrase in a secure location. Tick the checkbox and press on ‘Let’s go!’

And we’re done creating our second wallet! At this point, your screen should look similar to the image in ‘Expected output’. You should see 100 HBAR tokens in your wallet - these tokens are airdropped into our wallet at the point of wallet creation (only applicable for testnet accounts). You might need to press on the refresh button on the top right corner of your wallet to reflect the changes.

Make sure that there’s the pink border along the top of your wallet that states “You are currently using testnet”. If you don’t see the pink border, it is likely that you have accidentally created a mainnet wallet instead.

Note: if your testnet wallet does not receive any HBAR tokens (i.e. balance shown is – or 0, that is FINE as well. Please proceed to the next step.
Expected output
Step 13: Importing Hedera Developer Portal Testnet Account
In HashPack, besides creating a new account, we can also import an existing account. Let’s try that out in this step - we’ll be importing our testnet account that was created using the Hedera Developer Portal.
Follow these steps to import our Hedera Developer Portal testnet account:
  1. In HashPack, press on the menu icon (three horizontal bars) and press on ‘Add Account’
  2. On the next screen, tick the ‘Testnet account’ checkbox and press on ‘I already have a wallet’, followed by ‘Import private key’
  3. Open up your Hedera Developer Portal tab. Copy the ED25519 DER Encoded Private Key and paste it into the field in the current HashPack window. If you encounter the error “No accounts matching this key found”, it is likely that you forgot to tick the ‘Testnet account’ checkbox earlier
  4. Give this wallet the nickname of hedera dev portal so that we can easily differentiate between the two accounts
  5. After the window refreshes, you should see that your Hedera Developer Portal account has been imported into HashPack! We can tell by looking at the account ID under the wallet’s name (and the balance is now 10,000 HBAR too). Refer to the image in ‘Expected output’ for a reference
Expected output
Step 14: Transferring HBAR Tokens
Let’s do one last task before we end this quest - transfer HBAR tokens between our two accounts! The HashPack wallet is capable of storing multiple accounts. To view this, press on the menu icon and press on ‘Switch Account’. In the drop down menu, you should be able to see that there are 2 wallets available - the first being the wallet we created in Step 12 and the second being the Hedera Developer Portal account we imported in Step 13. 
For your final task, you’ll need to transfer 400 HBAR tokens from your hedera dev portal wallet to your other wallet. These are the steps required to complete the task:
  1. In HashPack, change to the wallet created in Step 12. Copy its account ID (hint: you can hover over the wallet name to copy the accountId). It does not matter whether you copy the address with or without checksum
  2. Once you’ve copied the account ID, switch the account back to hedera dev portal
  3. Press ‘Send’ and paste the account ID into the field. Input 400 into the HBAR field
  4. Confirm and send the transaction

After a few seconds, HashPack will refresh and you’ll see that the HBAR balance of the hedera dev portal wallet has been decreased by the amount you transferred (and a little more due to paying gas fees). If you change the current wallet to the other wallet, you’ll see that its balance is now 500. Refer to the image in ‘Expected output’ for a reference.

Awesome! To recap the last few steps - we just used HashPack, a GUI, to create and import accounts as well as transfer tokens from one account to another. 

Note: incase you’re wondering what a checksum is, it is a feature to help improve the security and accuracy of transactions on the network by helping to prevent manual data entry mistakes and address similar errors. The added letters are completely optional; i.e. the number-only address still works without the added checksum. Refer here if you would like to find out more about account checksums.

In the next quest, we’ll explore how we can do the same thing (i.e. create an account and transfer HBAR between accounts), but programmatically instead. By programmatically, we mean creating a script and sending off API calls to the Hedera network, achieving whatever we just did, but using code instead of a GUI. Exciting stuff!

Step 15: Summary
We’ve covered quite a lot in this quest so give yourself a pat on the back! Let’s go through a summary of some of the points covered:
  • There are 2 types of nodes in the Hedera network - consensus nodes and mirror nodes.   Consensus nodes are full nodes that actively participate in the consensus process. Mirror nodes are nodes that store a copy of the network's transaction history and provide access to the data; they do not participate in the consensus process
  • HBAR is the native cryptocurrency of the Hedera network. It is used to pay for transaction fees and network services
  • Accounts are stored on the public ledger and hold HBAR. Each account consists of several components
  • Transactions are requests sent by a client to a consensus node in the network to be processed
  • Nested transactions is a type of transaction that involves grouping multiple transactions together and treating them as a single unit
  • Scheduled transactions is a transaction with the ability to collect the required signatures on a Hedera network in preparation for its execution
  • Queries are requests for information from the network
  • Confirmations are produced after transactions have been submitted to the network. There are three types of confirmations available - receipts, records and state proofs (coming soon)
  • State & History - in Hedera, there is a difference between these two concepts; this is reflected in the different functions that the mainnet nodes and mirror nodes play
  • Hedera Developer Portal is used by developers to create testnet accounts. Testnet accounts created by the portal are given 10,000 test HBAR every 24 hours
  • HashPack wallet can be used to create and import accounts, as well as transfer tokens from one account to another

Screenshot
Open up your HashPack wallet (both the web app and Chrome extension versions are fine). Make sure that the current wallet selected is the wallet with 500 HBAR tokens. If your wallet has slightly less than 500 HBAR tokens, that is fine as well. Take a full screen screenshot of your HashPack window/extension. Your screenshot should include your taskbar / dock as well.

Your screenshot should show:
  • your full screen, including your taskbar (for Windows and Linux) / dock (for MacOS)
  • HashPack window/extension showing an account with ~500 HBAR balance
  • make sure that all parts visible in ‘Expected output’ are also visible in your screenshot!

When labeling your screenshot, make sure to follow the format provided (remembering to replace “yourstackupname” with your StackUp username): C64a_Q2_yourstackupname.png.

Refer to ‘Expected output’ if you are unsure.

By submitting the quest, please note that our StackUp Policy prohibits the use of multiple accounts by a single user and the submission of copied work.
